        "trailText":"Chief executive's comments on first day of official share trading come as CWU union prepares to announce plans for industrial action",
        "headline":"Royal Mail boss Moya Greene calls for protection from strikes",
        "body":"<p>Royal Mail boss Moya Greene has called for \"protections\" from strikes as more than 100,000 postal workers prepare to announce plans for industrial action that could take place as soon as 23 October.</p><p>In an interview to mark <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/oct/15/royal-mail-shares-official-trading-investors\" title=\"\">Royal Mail's first official day as a public company</a>, Greene said: \"We need to start thinking about what sort of protections do we need as a company from our people, from what has been probably too quick an approach to resort to industrial action.</p><p>\"I just think we need to look at alternative ways to resolve disputes,\" she told ITV News.</p><p>Greene's comments come as the Communication Workers Union (CWU) prepares to announce the result of a strike ballot on Wednesday.</p><p>The CWU, which represents more than 115,000 of Royal Mail's 150,000 employees, said it was \"confident\" that its members will vote on Wednesday for industrial action.</p><p>It is understood that <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/13/postal-workers-strike-ballot-pay-conditions\" title=\"\">the union has already made tentative plans for days of disruption in the run-up to Christmas.</a></p><p>Dave Ward, the CWU's deputy general secretary, said: \"The Royal Mail share price has soared further today, bringing more proof that the company was undervalued by the government's City mates.</p><p>\"The taxpayer has lost over £1bn already in this bungled fire sale of a cherished national institution. Postal workers cannot trade their shares for three years and they are far more concerned about their jobs than the share price. We're confident our members will return a yes vote in tomorrow's ballot result for strike action, strengthening our position to secure a deal on protecting jobs, services and terms and conditions in the company.\"</p><p>Royal Mail's shares have soared by 44% since the government privatised the 500-year-old company on Friday.</p><p>The share price spike means the 690,000 people who managed to buy a stake in the company have made paper profits of more than £300.</p><p>It also means the government could have collected at least more than £800m more for the taxpayer if it had sold the shares at 450p rather than 330p. The shares are currently changing hands at 481p.</p><p>Adrian Bailey, the Labour chair of the business department select committee, said the share price surge \"vindicated\" concerns the committee raised when it questioned the business secretary, Vince Cable, last week.</p><p>\"At the meeting last week it's fair to say that members of the committee had one view and the secretary of state had another,\" Bailey said. \"The share price movements have vindicated the concerns of the committee members. Let's see where the price settles.\"</p><p>Bailey said the committee will also call Lazard, the investment bank that advised the government on how to price Royal Mail, to answer questions about its valuation advice.</p><p>The National Audit Office, the public spending watchdog, and the public accounts committee will also investigate allegations that Royal Mail was sold too cheaply.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420028784|2013-10-16T18:19:29Z|95bb86207ed6dd9e793cca4c84ae6b1444c3a86c -->",
