      "id":"commentisfree/2013/oct/16/postal-workers-strike-royal-mail-cwu-privatisation",
      "sectionId":"commentisfree",
      "sectionName":"Comment is free",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-16T16:00:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Postal workers' strike: Royal Mail should expect a battle royal | Gregor Gall",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/16/postal-workers-strike-royal-mail-cwu-privatisation",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/16/postal-workers-strike-royal-mail-cwu-privatisation",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<strong>Gregor Gall: </strong>The CWU may have lost the battle on privatisation, but industrial action will send a powerful message on pay and conditions",
        "headline":"Postal workers' strike: Royal Mail should expect a battle royal",
        "body":"<p>It's been a case of third time unlucky for the <a href=\"http://www.cwu.org/\" title=\"\">postal workers' union (CWU)</a>. It defeated the privatisation of Royal Mail in 1994 under the Tories and again in 2009 under Labour. Despite employing similar tactics of political lobbying and industrial action, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/video/2013/oct/15/royal-mail-trading-london-stock-exchange-video\" title=\"\">on Tuesday the company was floated on the stock exchange</a>. The share price has risen by almost 50% since then. And just a<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/oct/10/royal-mail-refusenik-share-offer\" title=\"\"> tiny handful of postal workers refused to take up the free share offer open to them</a>.</p><p>Some have proclaimed it's \"game over\" for the CWU and any planned industrial action – the <a href=\"http://www.newstatesman.com/business/2013/09/royal-mail-sell-thatcherism-lives?\" title=\"\">left-leaning New Statesman pronounced striking now was \"a little bit pointless\".</a></p><p>Yes, the CWU was caught on the hop by a sell-off timetable that was brought forward, a bargain basement initial share price and having to take extra time to fully check the accuracy of its membership records in order to avoid a possible high court injunction to stop any action.</p><p>But exactly the opposite is now true. So while industrial action is extremely unlikely to bring Royal Mail back into public hands any time soon – especially as the <a href=\"http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2013/10/how-labour-could-still-save-royal-mail-privatisation\" title=\"\">Labour leadership reneged on its own party policy within days of it being set </a>, it is still vital. This is because it is necessary to allow the workforce to have the chance to contest what privatisation turns out be. And, that's why <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/oct/16/royal-mail-workers-vote-favour-strike-privatisation\" title=\"\">postal workers today voted by 4-1 for action on a high turnout</a>.</p><p>First, there is the most obvious sense in which the jobs and conditions of Royal Mail workers are under even greater threat. The company has continually been in a state of being prepared for privatisation so some 50,000 jobs have been cut in the last decade. But just before the flotation, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/oct/09/royal-mail-warns-thousands-job-losses\" title=\"\">Royal Mail announced that further job losses were inevitable</a>: \"The company will employ fewer people in the future, whoever owns it\". For those that remain, not only will the work now get that much harder and the days that much longer, but new workers will be recruited on casualised, zero-hours contracts. This will undermine the conditions of existing workers.</p><p>So the CWU is absolutely right to be pushing for a long-term agreement to secure the jobs and pensions of its Royal Mail members as well as to improve their pay and conditions. The three-year deal on offer from Royal Mail is not up to the job. That is why the CWU is demanding a 10-year deal.</p><p>Second, and as has inevitably happened with previous privatisations, individual shareholders soon sell up after making a quick buck and the vast majority of shares are then held by institutional investors. So the 36% of shares given initially to the small investors will migrate to the institutions, meaning that the pressure to ramp up profits will grow, especially if venture capitalists and private equity get involved.</p><p>The effect of taking industrial action will be to create both industrial relations and share price instability – two things institutional investors like least. In the case of Royal Mail, investors know that the postal workers' action bites and bites fast. They have the ability not only to bring the postal system to a halt through strike action but to do this at the busiest time of the year (the runup to Christmas) and there is no ready alternative postal system at hand. Then, through industrial action short of a strike, by refusing to process the mail of competitors that have bought access to Royal Mail's network, they can hit revenues for a second time.</p><p>This means their action will be strategic and powerful.</p><p>Having failed in her bid to get <a href=\"http://news.sky.com/story/1110146/royal-mail-staff-reject-pay-and-bonus-offer\" title=\"\">her staff to work in partnership with management to create a \"world-beating company\"</a> Royal Mail's chief executive, Moya Greene, is obviously worried enough to <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/oct/15/royal-mail-cross-picket-lines-strike\" title=\"\">offer £300 to each worker to refuse to strike or cross a picket line</a>.</p><p>In the last four national strikes (1988, 1996, 2007, 2009), postal workers have been unbeaten. You'd have to go back as far as 1971 or find their last defeated national strike. Royal Mail is now ready for its battle royal.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420162740|2013-10-16T18:19:29Z|813c2439ffdde19dc9aaa74517fbb71634eb4c81 -->",
